The Magicians Monopoly Rules

One player becomes the Banker, who distributes assets from the Bank to the players. Only the player in question can use their money, money can only be lent via the Banker. Each player receives two $500, four $100, one $50, one $20, two $10, one $5, and five $1. Each player begins the game with $1500.
On a player's turn, he or she must roll the dice and move his or her token forward the number of spaces as rolled on the dice.If the player lands on an unowned property, he or she may buy it for the price listed on that property's space. If he or she agrees to buy it, he or she pays the Bank the amount shown on the property space and receives the deed for that property.If the player lands on an unmortgaged property owned by another player, he or she pays rent to that person, as specified on the property's deed. It is the property owner's responsibility to demand rent, and he or she has until the beginning of the second following player's turn to do so.If the player lands on his or her own property, or on property which is owned by another player but currently mortgaged, nothing happens.
If the player lands on Luxury Tax/Super Tax, he or she must pay the Bank $100.If the player lands on Income Tax he or she must pay the Bank either $200.
If the player lands on the Dungeon space, he or she is "Just Visiting". No penalty applies.If the player lands on the Go to the dungeon square, he or she must move his token directly to the dungeon.
Players may not loan money to other players. Only the Bank can loan money.If a player skips another player's turn and is caught, the turn is transferred back to the player whose turn was skipped.
The only way to win is if the player remains the only player with the money

description.text:
This is my recreation of the "Waterlily" portable wind and water generator. My current prototype has not been tested in the water yet, as I haven't quite figured out a decent way to waterproof the motor yet. With proper electronics, it should be able to charge a cell phone or other USB device using nothing but wind or moving water.

For those interested, the model files are included so you can make your own mods, customizations, or improvements. Be sure to share the cool things you make!

Printer Brand:

PrintrBot

Printer:

Simple Black

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20

Notes:

The propeller may require supports for some users, but I personally didn't need them to get a nice print.

After printing, only a few things are required to get a functioning wind/water turbine. 1st, a motor with 24mm outer diameter must be inserted into the bottom mount. Once that is done, the propeller can be slipped onto the shaft, maybe with a dab of glue if needed. Once that is done, the crossbar support can be glued in at the top. It's orientation doesn't really matter, but it generally looks best lined up with either of the bottom crossbeams. This doesn't need to be pushed down particularly hard, just enough to prevent the propeller from spinning off center.
Then comes wiring, which isn't very hard in this case. 1st, you will need a boost converter to boost the lower voltage up to 5v, so a charger can use it.
(this looks like it should work, there are other models if you need a higher current limit: https://www.amazon.com/Yeeco-Converter-Regulator-Directive-Ultra-small/dp/B014LX94IU/ref=sr_1_6?ie=UTF8&qid=1494553944&sr=8-6&keywords=5v%2Bboost%2Bconverter&th=1).
You will want to wire up + to + and - to -. This isn't entirely obvious on the motor side, so spin the propeller while it's hooked up to a multimeter and check the polarity. That's it! You're done and ready to go!*

If you are going to use this in running water, you might want to figure out a way waterproof the electronics, If you want them to work that is.

Side note. If you want the motor I am using right now, this is what I have found:
https://www.amazon.com/uxcell-x27mm-3V-12V-20000RPM-Massager/dp/B014818SPA/ref=sr_1_10?ie=UTF8&qid=1494554248&sr=8-10&keywords=24mm+dc+motor

This model was designed around I motor I had that I knew worked, and an amazing propeller I found made by the user "dreyfusduke". It is an amazing model, and what really makes this thing work. After I had my starting parameters, I built a shell around the components in a shape that somewhat resembled the Waterlily, just because that's what I wanted to make it look like.

For anyone interested, the blender files have been included in the download, so anyone adventurous enough can give it a go. Modify it to your heart's content, and maybe give me a suggestion if you made a improvement that you think should be standard.

comments.text: Why not increase the size slightly and put a nema stepper motor inside the cone of the propeller? As long as you have the motor housed such that water will pass completely over the motor housing without getting in then further waterproofing shouldn't be necessary. description.text: Having to poke your finger into the Printrbot Simple to hit the reset button got to be annoying so I created a mechanism to reset the machine from the outside. (Be kind its my first design)

You may need to use a nail file to clean up sags on the inside of the pivot. I used a small roll pin to join the two parts together. Line up the arm in the pivot and drill a small hole thru both parts, make sure the hole is smaller then the diameter of the roll pin, then take the two pieces apart and drill the arm larger then the pin. Reassemble the pieces and drive the roll pin thru both holes and cut it flush. You can possibly use a small cotter pin, a small nail or a piece of paper clip for joining instead of the roll pin but you have to bend or glue them to ensure that the metal part is securely fastened. You don't want anything metal to fall out and contact the circuit board.

Yes, it's that great super hero from the Great Lakes Avengers..... err.... Great Lakes X-Men..... uhhh..... Great Lakes Initiative.... or is it that they are back to being the Avengers???? Whatever the team is called, Doorman is there for them, being a doorway and all that. With his newly added powers from Dethurge, he now has a 'Death Sense'.

Pic taken from the Great Lakes X-mas Special (2006)

MakerBot's T-Rex Skeleton is a masterpiece. Too bad MakerBot refused to fix some obvious issues. Thus I made the following fixes to make the model printable:

--I fixed tail parts A and B. Both original parts, particularly B, were broken at the second piece. It made B utterly unprintable and A very fragile, if successfully printed. I solidified both parts.

--I separate arms, tails and all ribs. These tall and thin parts are very susceptible to being knocked over by the nozzle as it moves from part to part. In addition the frequent retraction makes these parts (if successfully printed) very poor quality and very stringy in-between. Printing individually is the way to go.

--I merged the neck H clip into the H clip file. It's a mystery why the original designer didn't.

--I included a merged one-piece base for those whose bed is large enough. No more seam on the base.

Printing note:

--Only left arm and ribs are included. Mirror them to print the right counterparts.

--Using 8mm of brim is strongly recommended for all parts except the H clips. It is easy to remove so no worries.

--You need very strong bed adhesion. On my Prusa i3 MK2S, the naked bed simply doesn't offer enough adhesion. The glue stick worked occasionally but mostly not. My best friend is Aqua Net Super Hold hairspray. It is great because 1) adhesion is stronger than ever and I didn't have a single part peeled off; 2) after removing a printed part you don't need to do anything but can just go on printing the next part. Don't buy it from Amazon. It's sold for only $3 at Walgreens! https://www.walgreens.com/store/c/aqua-net-professional-hair-spray-extra-super-hold-3-unscented/ID=prod5458027-product (disclaimer: I have no financial relationship with Walgreens).

--For the really thin and tall parts such as the first and last few ribs and tail part D and the arms, slow the printer down to allow more cooling time and improve printing quality.

One more thing: ProtoParadigm's Woodchip PLA has the dried-bone color perfect for this print. http://www.protoparadigm.com/ingeo-pla/woodchip-PLA-1KG (disclaimer: I have no financial relationship with ProtoParadigm).

Happy printing!

comments.text: You did a great job on this!  I have a trick for printing long thin parts (or small parts).  I made a "doughnut" in sketchup - 5mm x 5mm with a 2mm hole.  .  When I want to print a tall thin part, I add this doughnut and scale it the same Z height as my part (keep X and Y the same). Now it's a cylinder  Then I put the part in the center and put the cylinder in front of it.  Duplicate the cylinder and move the copy behind the part.   Now you have 3 parts.  This gives the layers time to cool properly.  Collect the cylinders, because they have holes in them, so they are actually beads!  When you get a big bag full of them, take them down to the local school and give them to the art teacher.

title: Bolt Together AR AK grip adapter.

description.text:
The finishing touch to complete that Ar15 7.62x39 build with a Bolt lower. So you've got a PSA side chargine upper, a lower with no bolt release, and a crazy RIS? You've basically just made an Ar into an AK, but you want to ditch the A2 grip? This is the answer.

This adapter will replace the grip tang on a bolt together ar15 lower reciever, and allow an Ak grip to be installed instead. The only modification required from standard installation is that your safety detent spring needs to be shortened or replaced, as the AK grip does not have a space for the other end.

Since it can not use an AK's grip screw or reciver tang, new hardware is required. I made the extension for a 1/4 - 3in machine screw and nut, available at Harbor Freight, but any 3inch long bolt will work, and there is also runout space behind it to allow for a 3 1/2 inch long bolt to be used. Simply glue the nut in place, or shim it, to prevent rotation, or you might never get it back off.

description.text:
Hey, everyone!

This page is to provide an update space for the rules for our 3D-print-and-play game, OpenTactics. We're running a number of collections here on Thingiverse that will catalog the various sets, characters, and terrain that we design for the game, but this space in particular will hold the core rules PDF that we'll be updating as changes occur and new material gets added. Ultimately, we want OpenTactics to allow you to create your own characters, either from our library of models, models you like made by other designers here on Thingiverse or by established manufacturers, or custom models you make yourself. Speaking to that, if you do design your own stuff and want to contribute it to the game, let us know and we'll look at adding it to the growing canon. We'd really like for this to be a community-driven, open source gaming experience, with players and designers sharing their ideas.

In addition, the activation counters included here (totally optional) can be used in place of the usual five you would use, with each granting a special effect when played. SWORD (bonus re-roll to OFF die during the re-roll phase), SHIELD (bonus re-roll to DEF die during the re-roll phase), BOOT (+1 move distance during a movement, charge, or deployment), ARROW (+1 range value during a Ballistic or Arcane assault), and one blank counter that gives no special benefit.

Definitely expect files here to change, but I'll try and keep an update log going in the comments, so if you're interested, maybe throw a watch on the page. This is definitely a beta stage in the game, but we've had some fantastic play tests so far and really want to hone this one into something special.

STEAM WORKSHOPS: OpenTactics is now public on the Steam Workshops for Tabletop Simulator! If you have that program and you would rather play there than in meatspace, we plan to continue updating with any content we put here. Tabletop Simulator is really fantastic, and it makes this game all the more accessible to those without access to 3D printing.

We've set up a Patreon page for anyone who's interested in helping to fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like OpenTactics, Pocket-Tactics, Discord, and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...)

Enjoy!

This is a spherical keycap with a Cherry MX stem. The design is meant to be similar to the SA keycap profile. This design has been around for a while since I made it available on Geekhack, and it has had a few hundred downloads there since I posted it. I'm sure the Thingiverse crowd will find plenty of ways to customize it.

This seems to be the only spherical profile cap I can find on this site. Most everything here has a DCS or OEM Cherry profile. This is designed to be slightly taller than a DSA cap, and slightly shorter than an SA cap. A figure of this comparison is included on this page. This means that there is plenty of room to add "stuff" to the face of the cap (letters, numbers, tiny robot faces, etc.) without negatively impacting the overall profile of your board.

The face of the cap is supported by some filleted bridges which will clear the casing of your MX switch upon keypress. This also improves the structural characteristics of the keycap for those of us that have fingers like tiny hammers.

Text can easily be added to the face of the cap. I have included an example I made with a quote from American Psycho in the files.

Keycap stems are tricky to print, as they tend to demand tight tolerance. This was designed with a little extra tolerance for thermoplastic expansion. If you decide to use it often, print a quick one out first to see if the cruciform fits snugly onto your switches. The versions depicted were created on a laser sintering printer, rather than an FDM printer.

Enjoy! Please report back any makes or mods of this design so I can see my stuff in action.

To be functional, some filtering material (sponge, foam, etc.) needs to be glued to the knobbed side. Then slide it onto the very bottom edge of any 6mm feeding tube for 1.75mm filament (potentially 3mm as well) with the filtering material facing incoming filament.

As the filament is drawn out by the extruder, it will pass through the filtering material and any dust will wipe off (if the filtering material is dense enough).

title: Make your own thread for Novice - simplified

description.text:
Was trying to make thread on SCAD without depending on libraries, but find every sample code on Thingiverse too complicate to understand, since they're all using polyhedron. So first I created a simple way using linear extrude to draw thread. Next using the same code but modified to use polyhedron.

Linear Extrude was easy to understand, learn and replicate without complicated formulas. Certainly not the fastest rendering time. Sample code took 4mins to render.

Polyhedron formulas is very unfriendly. But I tried to make it as simple and easy to understand as possible. Sample code took 1 min 45 secs to render.

Polyhedron output quality is far lot better. So polyhedron wins.
No choice but have to learn the complicated stuff.

description.text:
One of the feet on my 13-inch retina mbp is missing. Looking up for a replacement or an alternative for some time, but the result is not so good: either is not available in China, or is not suitable for 13-rmbp.

So I do it my self.
The 13-rmbp's foot is very thin and is hollow inside, like a shell, so as to absorb the shock. And there is a central pole to bear the weight of the mbp.

I followed this principle. Although the PLA is harder than the rubber-like material used the old foot, I think the similar design can provide the similar function, or part of it.

After printing, use double sided tape the fix the foot in position. I replaced two feet together, so there is no problem on keeping a balance. So, I suggest to replace two front or two back feet in pair, or all four feet together.

I just could not find a case for my Xiaomi 20000mAh battery pack (Powerbank) so i created my own.

-The case features a hole for the button so you can see the charge of the Powerbank.
-The case is made to be tough (1,5mm walls and bottom)
-Leaving the cap on will not be a problem since you have full access to the USB ports for charging your devices as well as the powerbank itself.

title: OpenForge 2.0 Cut Stone Diagonal,Curved and Corridor Half Walls

description.text:
I Love Devon Jones' OpenForge 2.0 work and have printed a number of his items out in the last few days that I have had a 3D printer. I like the half height tiles as they require less material, print faster and allow the GM/DM to observe character/item placement better. Only corner and straight wall sections were currently available in the half height tiles (that I am aware of), so I used Blender (very badly-with 2 hours youtube training) to modify existing Curved, Diagonal and Corridor wall sections into the presented half height versions.

I made the Curved and Diagonal tiles on square bases so they are reversible (ie concave/convex for the curved walls and mirrored on the diagonal)

Please note that as I am a new Blender user (with limited experience), the brick layout may be off by half a brick compared to Devon's work (ie a full brick will align with a half brick on an adjoining tile instead of another full brick), however, this is not really noticeable.

See attached photos for example layouts. I print in black, give a quick brush over in dark grey then dry brush light grey for highlights as I am a lazy painter. I have attached magnetic bases to these photo examples and they work well. Second photo is just an example way of making wider corridors using standard wall sections as standard corridor can be a little tight. I am not experienced enough in Blender to really make wider corridors myself.
